{"source_key":"sha256-852da461b9759bc2736926d9891eb9a3","record_index":9869,"record_hash":"sha256:c3f8ed3e7a47efc893f0343621597c1861d976638cb3e055b37c2b04bc3186ad","timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:34:49.688Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"user","text":"<subagent_notification>\n{\"agent_path\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"status\":{\"completed\":\"**Short version:** model the handoff as a durable, inspectable state transition, not just a chat summary. Use three layers: `checkpoint log`, `handoff envelope`, and `long-term memory`.\\n\\n**Findings**\\n\\n1. **LangGraph has the cleanest prior art for checkpoint semantics.**  \\n   LangGraph persists graph state as checkpoints inside a `thread_id`; this enables resume, human review, replay, branching, and fault recovery. It also stores per-node pending writes so completed work does not rerun after partial failure.  \\n   Source: [LangGraph persistence docs](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/persistence), [checkpoint reference](https://reference.langchain.com/python/langgraph/checkpoints/)\\n\\n   **Implication:** a CLI handoff should have a stable `thread_id` or `session_id`, plus monotonic checkpoints. Don’t just save “current transcript”; save recoverable step state.\\n\\n2. **Separate conversation state from cross-session memory.**  \\n   LangGraph explicitly distinguishes thread-local checkpoint state from a broader store for memory shared across threads. Checkpoints are for “where this run is”; stores are for “what this agent/user/project knows.”  \\n   Source: [LangGraph persistence: memory store](https://docs.langchain.com/oss/python/langgraph/persistence)\\n\\n   **Implication:** handoff payload should include:\\n   - current task state\\n   - recent transcript or compacted summary\\n   - tool results needed to continue\\n   - links/IDs to durable project memory  \\n   \\n   Avoid dumping every memory into the handoff.\\n\\n3. **OpenAI’s Agents SDK treats handoff as a tool call with optional structured metadata.**  \\n   Handoffs can attach schema-validated input like `reason`, `priority`, or `summary`; by default the receiving agent sees prior conversation history unless filtered.  \\n   Source: [OpenAI Agents SDK handoffs](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-python/handoffs/), [JS handoffs](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-js/guides/handoffs/)\\n\\n   **Implication:** design a first-class `handoff` command/event with a typed envelope, not a loose prose note. Example fields: `reason`, `goal`, `next_action`, `blocked_on`, `files_touched`, `commands_run`, `risk_notes`.\\n\\n4. **OpenAI Conversations/Responses provide durable provider-side conversation IDs, but they’re not enough for tool handoff.**  \\n   Conversations persist messages, tool calls, tool outputs, and other items under a durable ID; `previous_response_id` chains state.  \\n   Source: [OpenAI conversation state](https://developers.openai.com/api/docs/guides/conversation-state)\\n\\n   **Implication:** provider conversation IDs are useful references, but a CLI should still own its local state model. Otherwise handoff portability, audit, and replay are hostage to one provider’s storage.\\n\\n5. **Session compaction is now treated as a handoff primitive.**  \\n   OpenAI Agents JS explicitly supports compaction before archiving or handoff.  \\n   Source: [OpenAI Agents JS sessions](https://openai.github.io/openai-agents-js/guides/sessions/)\\n\\n   **Implication:** add an explicit `compact-for-handoff` path. The output should be deterministic-ish, editable, and saved alongside the raw event log.\\n\\n6. **MCP is useful for exposing context, not for owning durable conversation state.**  \\n   MCP standardizes resources, tools, prompts, roots, sampling, elicitation, progress, logging, etc. It uses stateful connections, but the spec is about protocol interaction, not checkpoint storage.  \\n   Source: [MCP specification](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/specification/2025-11-25), [MCP resources](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/docs/concepts/resources)\\n\\n   **Implication:** use MCP to expose handoff resources like `session://.../summary`, `checkpoint://...`, or `workspace://...`; don’t expect MCP itself to solve persistence.\\n\\n7. **Claude Code’s memory model is pragmatic: markdown files, loaded selectively.**  \\n   Claude Code uses project memory files, imports, scoped rules, and an auto-memory directory. Its `MEMORY.md` acts as a concise index; topic files are read on demand.  \\n   Source: [Claude Code memory docs](https://code.claude.com/docs/en/memory)\\n\\n   **Implication:** for CLI handoff, boring files beat magical memory. Keep a small handoff index plus linked artifacts. Human-editable markdown/JSON is a feature.\\n\\n8. **Context editing confirms the pattern: preserve important tool results before pruning.**  \\n   Anthropic’s context editing can clear old tool results while giving the model a chance to save important information to memory files.  \\n   Source: [Claude context editing](https://platform.claude.[REDACTED:entropy])\\n\\n   **Implication:** when trimming transcript/tool output, write a provenance-backed summary first. Never silently drop tool results that affect next actions.\\n\\n9. **Research points toward structured, provenance-aware memory.**  \\n   Recent work argues memory is a write-manage-read loop, not a blob of chat history. Memori frames memory as compact structured triples/summaries; MemLineage adds provenance/lineage to prevent untrusted memories from later justifying sensitive actions.  \\n   Sources: [Memory for Autonomous LLM Agents survey](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.07670), [Memori](https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.19935), [MemLineage](https://arxiv.org/abs/2605.14421)\\n\\n   **Implication:** every remembered fact should carry source, timestamp, author/agent, confidence, and derivation. Treat memory from tool output, user instruction, and model inference differently.\\n\\n**Recommended CLI Design**\\n\\nUse this shape:\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"handoff_id\\\": \\\"uuid\\\",\\n  \\\"thread_id\\\": \\\"stable-session-id\\\",\\n  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"monotonic-or-content-addressed-id\\\",\\n  \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"timestamp\\\",\\n  \\\"from_agent\\\": \\\"agent-id\\\",\\n  \\\"to_agent\\\": \\\"optional-agent-id\\\",\\n  \\\"goal\\\": \\\"what we are trying to finish\\\",\\n  \\\"state\\\": {\\n    \\\"status\\\": \\\"in_progress | blocked | ready_for_review\\\",\\n    \\\"next_action\\\": \\\"single concrete next step\\\",\\n    \\\"open_questions\\\": [],\\n    \\\"risks\\\": []\\n  },\\n  \\\"artifacts\\\": {\\n    \\\"transcript_ref\\\": \\\"path-or-uri\\\",\\n    \\\"summary_ref\\\": \\\"path-or-uri\\\",\\n    \\\"tool_log_ref\\\": \\\"path-or-uri\\\",\\n    \\\"workspace_diff_ref\\\": \\\"path-or-uri\\\"\\n  },\\n  \\\"provenance\\\": {\\n    \\\"commands_run\\\": [],\\n    \\\"files_read\\\": [],\\n    \\\"files_changed\\\": [],\\n    \\\"external_sources\\\": []\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\nMy take: build the durable source of truth as an append-only local event/checkpoint log, then generate compact handoff summaries from it. Summaries are convenient; logs are truth.\"}}\n</subagent_notification>","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-20T18:34:49.688Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"message","role":"user"}}}